11 “SECTION 16. ORS 673.625 is amended to read:
12 “673.625. (1) Every applicant for a license as a tax consultant and every applicant for licensing
13 as a tax preparer must:
14 “(a) Be 18 years of age or older;
15 “(b) Possess a high school diploma or a modified diploma or have passed an equivalency exam-
16 ination;
17 “(c) Present evidence satisfactory to the State Board of Tax Practitioners that the applicant has
18 successfully completed at least 80 hours in basic personal income tax law, theory and practice at a
19 school training session or educational institution approved by the board; and
20 “(d) Possess a preparer tax identification number issued by the Internal Revenue Service.
21 “(2) In addition to the requirements of subsection (1) of this section, every applicant for licens-
22 ing as a tax preparer must pass to the satisfaction of the board an examination. The examination
23 must be constructed in a manner that in the judgment of the board measures the applicant’s
24 knowledge of Oregon and federal personal income tax law, theory and practice.
25 “(3) In addition to the requirements of subsection (1) of this section, every applicant for licens-
26 ing as a tax consultant must:
27 “(a) Present evidence satisfactory to the board of active employment, as described in ORS
28 673.615 (2), as a tax preparer or employment in this or another state in a capacity that is, in the
29 judgment of the board equivalent to that of a tax preparer or tax consultant, for not less than a
30 cumulative total of 1,100 hours during at least two of the last five years. The board shall consider
31 certification by a tax consultant or person described in ORS 673.610 [(2) or (4)] (2), (4) or (7) that
32 the applicant was employed as a tax preparer under supervision for the period indicated in the
33 certificate to be satisfactory evidence of the applicant’s employment as a tax preparer for the period
34 indicated. If an applicant has worked less than a cumulative total of 1,100 hours in at least two
35 of the last five years, the board may consider the number of hours employed, the number of years
36 employed, the number of tax returns prepared and whether the work involved contributed directly
37 to the professional competence of the individual in determining if a tax preparer or tax consultant
38 has met the work experience requirement.
39 “(b) Pass to the satisfaction of the board an examination that is constructed in a manner that
40 in the judgment of the board measures the applicant’s knowledge of Oregon and federal personal
41 income tax law, theory and practice. The examination for a tax consultant’s license must be of a
42 more exacting nature and require higher standards of knowledge of personal income tax law, theory
43 and practice than the examination for a tax preparer’s license.
